and optical,

00:07:22.060 --> 00:07:23.610
and as we increase
the energies again,

00:07:23.610 --> 00:07:26.400
we get to x-ray, and
then to gamma ray.

00:07:26.400 --> 00:07:28.950
But what I think is worth pointing

00:07:28.950 --> 00:07:33.030
out here is this is
what our eyes can see.

00:07:33.030 --> 00:07:37.630
A very, very small swath of
the electromagnetic spectrum.

00:07:37.630 --> 00:07:41.220
It's very important,
because we all see it,

00:07:41.220 --> 00:07:45.400
but this is what Fermi can see.

00:07:45.400 --> 00:07:48.000
The amount of range
of wavelengths covered

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.160
by Fermi is enormously broad.

00:07:50.160 --> 00:07:53.750
So while it's all called
gamma ray, that band,

00:07:53.750 --> 00:07:57.530
that part of the electromagnetic
spectrum is extremely large.

00:07:57.530 --> 00:07:58.830
And why you care about this?

00:07:58.830 --> 00:08:03.200
Well, if you think about it, if
you take a photograph of your hand,

00:08:03.200 --> 00:08:04.870
you have a photograph of your hand.

00:08:04.870 --> 00:08:07.440
If you take an x-ray of your
hand, you see the bones.

00:08:07.440 --> 00:08:12.970
And as you view your hand or the
universe at different energies

00:08:12.970 --> 00:08:16.130
or different wavelengths, you
get different information,

00:08:16.130 --> 00:08:17.980 position:56%
and it's just the same in astronomy.

00:08:17.980 --> 00:08:23.450 position:56%
That if we view the universe in
gamma rays, we see different things.

00:08:23.450 --> 00:08:24.760
We focus on different things.

00:08:24.760 --> 00:08:28.920
We learn different things than
when we make our observation

00:08:28.920 --> 00:08:32.140
with the more traditional
x-ray and optical

00:08:32.140 --> 00:08:34.670
and infrared and radio wavelengths.

