00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:04.960
So how do we detect gamma rays?

00:09:04.960 --> 00:09:07.240
I told you we have a
really strange telescope.

00:09:07.240 --> 00:09:08.540
There's no mirrors in gamma rays,

00:09:08.540 --> 00:09:11.130
because the gamma rays would
just go straight through them.

00:09:11.130 --> 00:09:13.600
What you have to think about is
how gamma rays actually interact

00:09:13.600 --> 00:09:15.300
with matter, and you
might have heard

00:09:15.300 --> 00:09:19.380
of Einstein's famous
equation E equals MC squared.

00:09:19.380 --> 00:09:22.040
And what this is telling
us is that energy

00:09:22.040 --> 00:09:25.820
and matter are fundamentally
the same thing.

00:09:25.820 --> 00:09:30.180
C is the speed of light,
which is a very large number.

00:09:30.180 --> 00:09:35.880
So if you multiply mass by very
large number, it equals energy,

00:09:35.880 --> 00:09:39.540
but a very large amount of
energy, and what's special

00:09:39.540 --> 00:09:43.120
about the wavelength, the energy
of the gamma rays that we looked

00:09:43.120 --> 00:09:47.630
at in Fermi, is that there's enough
energy in each individual gamma ray

00:09:47.630 --> 00:09:52.230
to produce an electron and
the anti-particle to electron,

00:09:52.230 --> 00:09:54.530
the positron, in our detector.

00:09:54.530 --> 00:09:58.080
So we're using this phenomenon
to detect our gamma rays,

00:09:58.080 --> 00:10:00.380
and we're using them because
we're converting the gamma rays

00:10:00.380 --> 00:10:05.010
from energy into matter, and
then we're tracking the motion

00:10:05.010 --> 00:10:09.620
of that matter in our detector.

00:10:12.040 --> 00:10:13.920 position:56%
So large-area telescope is this box.

00:10:13.920 --> 00:10:16.670
So what happens is a
gamma ray comes in.

00:10:16.670 --> 00:10:19.200
It's minding its own business,
and the remarkable thing

00:10:19.200 --> 00:10:21.170
about gamma rays is that, really,

00:10:21.170 --> 00:10:23.290
the universe is very
transparent to gamma rays.

00:10:23.290 --> 00:10:25.640
So this gamma ray, well, I mean
that's just a line on the screen,

00:10:25.640 --> 00:10:30.730
but if it was a gamma ray, it
will have gone through millions

00:10:30.730 --> 00:10:32.030
and millions of light-years.

00:10:32.030 --> 00:10:34.950
It can go straight to our galaxy,
but as soon as it comes close

00:10:34.950 --> 00:10:36.660
to the earth, it's
just going to go splat

00:10:36.660 --> 00:10:38.970
because the atmosphere
will absorb it.

00:10:38.970 --> 00:10:42.310
If it hits our atmosphere
first, what will happen is

00:10:42.310 --> 00:10:45.380
that the gamma ray will
interact to produce an electron,

00:10:45.380 --> 00:10:48.510
and the anti-particle to
the electronic, the proton,

00:10:48.510 --> 00:10:51.500
indicated in those purple lines.

00:10:51.500 --> 00:10:55.950
Our detector contains
instrumentation

00:10:55.950 --> 00:10:58.620
that can precisely
measure the position

00:10:58.620 --> 00:11:00.170
of the electron and positron.

00:11:00.170 --> 00:11:02.880
So we measure the tracks of
the electron and positron,

00:11:02.880 --> 00:11:05.990
and by reconstructing where
those tracks came from,

00:11:05.990 --> 00:11:09.270
we can figure out where the
gamma ray turned into matter

00:11:09.270 --> 00:11:10.990
and where it must have come from.

00:11:10.990 --> 00:11:15.090
At the bottom of our detector,

00:11:15.090 --> 00:11:17.660
we have a material
node as a scintillator.

00:11:17.660 --> 00:11:22.090 position:56%
A scintillator produces an amount of
light that's related to the amount

00:11:22.090 --> 00:11:24.940
of energy that was deposited
in it, and from that,

00:11:24.940 --> 00:11:27.160
we can measure the
energy of the gamma ray.

00:11:27.160 --> 00:11:28.590
So now we know where
the gamma ray came

00:11:28.590 --> 00:11:34.690
from We know what it's energy was,
so we can, gamma ray by gamma ray,

00:11:34.690 --> 00:11:41.010
build up a picture of the gamma
ray sky, one gamma ray at a time,

00:11:41.010 --> 00:11:45.370 position:56%
making our gamma rate map deeper
and deeper and deeper with every day

00:11:45.370 --> 00:11:48.370
that the mission continues
to make observations.

00:11:48.370 --> 00:11:52.000
It's an extraordinary instrument.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:12:00.860
We have over a million channels
of electronics, but we power it,

00:12:00.860 --> 00:12:04.570
