So for the briefest moment, a lot
of people's hearts dropped totally

00:15:20.560 --> 00:15:23.060
into their chest, but
then of course,

00:15:23.060 --> 00:15:25.370
it was actually completely fine.

00:15:25.370 --> 00:15:28.700
And all that was really happening
here is there was a larger

00:15:28.700 --> 00:15:32.620
than normal amount of water
flow underneath the rocket

00:15:32.620 --> 00:15:37.660
that you flow water underneath a
rocket at launch to stop the pad

00:15:37.660 --> 00:15:39.860
from being destroyed,
we just happened

00:15:39.860 --> 00:15:42.360
to have a particularly
high water supply.

00:15:42.360 --> 00:15:43.660
So that isn't smoke.

00:15:43.660 --> 00:15:45.850
It's steam.

00:15:45.850 --> 00:15:50.110
Okay, so let me tell you a bit
more about we've actually seen.

00:15:50.110 --> 00:15:52.620
So this is our sky above 1 GeV.

00:15:52.620 --> 00:15:54.280
I've shown it to you before.

00:15:54.280 --> 00:15:57.400 position:56%
At GeV, is a billion electron volts.

00:15:57.400 --> 00:16:00.540
A GeV is a billion electron
volt, and an electron volt is

00:16:00.540 --> 00:16:03.600
about the energy of
normal optical photon.

00:16:03.600 --> 00:16:06.150
So what you're seeing here,
every single gamma ray

00:16:06.150 --> 00:16:11.120
in this image has an energy that
is a billion times the energy

00:16:11.120 --> 00:16:14.640
of the photons of light that
are entering our eyes right now.

00:16:15.770 --> 00:16:20.800 position:56%
But we got a broad energy range, so
I can also show you a map of our sky

00:16:20.800 --> 00:16:25.010
above 50 GeV, 50 billion
electron volts.

00:16:25.010 --> 00:16:28.560
And what we see in the sky
changes slightly just as it does

00:16:28.560 --> 00:16:33.580 position:56%
when you look at the sky in infrared
and you look at the sky in optical.

00:16:33.580 --> 00:16:35.230
Some objects go away.

00:16:35.230 --> 00:16:37.560
Some appear, but the
thing I really want you

00:16:37.560 --> 00:16:40.270 position:56%
to notice are those two large lobes.

00:16:40.270 --> 00:16:42.360
I think I can do this.

00:16:42.360 --> 00:16:45.460
Large lobes above here
and down here.

00:16:45.460 --> 00:16:49.300
These were completely unexpected.

00:16:50.430 --> 00:16:52.360
They're unusual, because
they're appearing

00:16:52.360 --> 00:16:53.660
at only the highest energies.

00:16:53.660 --> 00:16:55.950
That's telling us that
they're being produced

00:16:55.950 --> 00:16:59.810
by very high energy particles
are gamma rays are produced not

00:16:59.810 --> 00:17:01.590
by heating something up
to a very high energy,

00:17:01.590 --> 00:17:05.970
but by accelerating charged
particles to close to the speed

00:17:05.970 --> 00:17:10.500 position:56%
of light, and the more accelerated
particles get, the higher the energy

00:17:10.500 --> 00:17:12.320
of gamma rays that you produce.

00:17:12.320 --> 00:17:15.680
So if we see these large,
faint lobes appearing

00:17:15.680 --> 00:17:18.050
at the highest energies,
what it's telling us is

00:17:18.050 --> 00:17:21.970
that there's a population of
particles of electrons or protons,

00:17:21.970 --> 00:17:26.160
we don't know which, in our
galaxy that have accelerated

00:17:26.160 --> 00:17:28.460
to extremely high energies.

00:17:29.680 --> 00:17:32.920
These lobes are really
quite extraordinary.

00:17:32.920 --> 00:17:37.540
They loom over above and
below the galactic center,

00:17:37.540 --> 00:17:40.660
extending for 25,000
light years above

00:17:40.660 --> 00:17:44.310
and 25,000 light years
below the galactic plane.

00:17:44.310 --> 00:17:51.190 position:56%
If your eyes were sensitive to gamma
rays, the Fermi bubbles would extend

00:17:51.190 --> 00:17:52.760
over almost half the sky.

00:17:52.760 --> 00:17:55.490
They would absolutely dominate
the sky you see at night,

00:17:55.490 --> 00:17:59.440
and we had no idea that these
existed until we had Fermi,

00:17:59.440 --> 00:18:01.430
an instrument that was sensitive

00:18:01.430 --> 00:18:07.590
to the photons dominantly being
produced by the Fermi lobes

00:18:07.590 --> 00:18:12.100
over a field of view that's large
enough to map them completely.

00:18:12.100 --> 00:18:16.310
If you were to turn the
Fermi bubbles on their side,

00:18:16.310 --> 00:18:22.310 position:56%
they would envelop us, but they
don't, because they're perpendicular

00:18:22.310 --> 00:18:25.660
to the plane of our galaxy, and
of course, we lie in our galaxy.

00:18:25.660 --> 00:18:29.480
So we're -- well, you can
see the label of the sun.

00:18:29.480 --> 00:18:31.910
There's lots of things
extraordinary about this.

00:18:31.910 --> 00:18:36.400
The total amount of energy in the
Fermi bubbles is equal to somewhere

00:18:36.400 --> 00:18:42.960
between 1000 and 10,000 supernova
all going off at the same time.

00:18:42.960 --> 00:18:46.180 position:56%
The energies of the individual
gamma rays are extraordinarily high.

00:18:46.180 --> 00:18:49.940
This, I think, is one of
the most unexpected things

00:18:49.940 --> 00:18:51.520
that we could ever have found.

00:18:51.520 --> 00:18:53.570
So what do we think it is?

00:18:53.570 --> 00:18:57.230
Well, first, before I go to that,
let's -- another couple of --

00:18:57.230 --> 00:19:01.850
this is one of the early maps that
we used to find the Fermi bubbles,

00:19:01.850 --> 00:19:03.200
and there were two features.

00:19:03.200 --> 00:19:05.400
The first I've already described is

00:19:05.400 --> 00:19:10.100
that the Fermi bubbles have
higher energy gamma rays than most

00:19:10.100 --> 00:19:12.560
of the rest of the
emission in our galaxy.

00:19:12.560 --> 00:19:16.190
So they stand out when we
make a map of higher energies.

00:19:16.190 --> 00:19:17.680
They also have sharp edges.

00:19:17.680 --> 00:19:21.160
So the sharp edges are important,
because the sharp edges suggest

00:19:21.160 --> 00:19:23.810
that they were produced
by some transient event.

00:19:23.810 --> 00:19:26.820
That something happened that
produced a shock wave that went

00:19:26.820 --> 00:19:32.010
out into the intergalactic
medium, blowing up the bubbles.

00:19:32.010 --> 00:19:36.670
So now the question is, well,
what could that possibly be?

00:19:36.670 --> 00:19:43.980 position:56%
To think about this, you need to try
and imagine where is a good place

00:19:43.980 --> 00:19:46.060
to produce a lot of energy?

00:19:46.060 --> 00:19:48.030
Well, we know that the center

00:19:48.030 --> 00:19:52.770
of our galaxy contains a
supermassive black hole.

00:19:52.770 --> 00:19:54.070
It's not active at the moment.

00:19:54.070 --> 00:19:55.370
It's quiet.

00:19:55.370 --> 00:19:56.670
It's quiescent.

00:19:56.670 --> 00:19:58.610
We know it's there, because we
can see the pattern of the stars

00:19:58.610 --> 00:20:03.060
as they orbit the center
of our galaxy,

00:20:03.060 --> 00:20:06.110
but what the Fermi bubbles are
telling us is that somewhere

00:20:06.110 --> 00:20:09.960
between 1 to 3 million years ago,

00:20:09.960 --> 00:20:13.150
the center of our galaxy
was not quiet,

00:20:13.150 --> 00:20:14.480
and there are two possibilities.

00:20:14.480 --> 00:20:18.200
One is that the black
hole itself became active.

00:20:18.200 --> 00:20:20.470
That perhaps some star
has dropped in,

00:20:20.470 --> 00:20:23.790
and you had a large accretion
event that produced the same jets,

00:20:23.790 --> 00:20:27.580
the relativistic jets, the
particles moving close to the speed

00:20:27.580 --> 00:20:30.720
of light beamed into a
narrow jet was produced

00:20:30.720 --> 00:20:33.970
when this creation event happened.

00:20:33.970 --> 00:20:37.190
Or, perhaps, you have
a large burst of stars

00:20:37.190 --> 00:20:39.070
that all form at the same time.

00:20:39.070 --> 00:20:43.220
The large stars will live a very
short life and will go supernova

00:20:43.220 --> 00:20:44.850
at the same time, and
that's another way

00:20:44.850 --> 00:20:47.360
of producing enormous
burst of energy.

00:20:47.360 --> 00:20:48.900
Or perhaps we have both.

00:20:48.900 --> 00:20:54.240
That initially you have a large
burst of star formation followed

00:20:54.240 --> 00:20:57.650
by creation onto the black hole,
produce a jet that then continues

00:20:57.650 --> 00:21:02.410
to power and energize this
shock as it extends out.

00:21:02.410 --> 00:21:03.710
It's relatively recent.

00:21:03.710 --> 00:21:07.870
So once, 3 million years
ago, humans were on Earth.

00:21:07.870 --> 00:21:11.030
So in astronomical terms,
I mean, this happened like,

00:21:11.030 --> 00:21:13.750
you know, just the other week.

00:21:13.750 --> 00:21:18.250
So I think it's very exciting to
have concrete evidence that are

00:21:18.250 --> 00:21:19.830
at the center of our galaxy.

00:21:19.830 --> 00:21:23.120
The black hole at the center
of our galaxy did not behave

00:21:23.120 --> 00:21:25.830
in the recent past way
that we see it now.

00:21:25.830 --> 00:21:30.740
Okay, so let me tell you a little
bit about how we make observations.

00:21:30.740 --> 00:21:32.040
This is supposed be an animation.

00:21:32.040 --> 00:21:33.340
There we go.

00:21:33.340 --> 00:21:35.260
So we got a huge field of view.

00:21:35.260 --> 00:21:37.980
The field of view of our
instrument, we see about 20%

00:21:37.980 --> 00:21:39.430
of the sky at any instance.

00:21:39.430 --> 00:21:40.760
That's about what your
eye is [inaudible].

00:21:40.760 --> 00:21:46.030
So what we do is if you
imagine, you just look,

00:21:46.030 --> 00:21:47.330
you're going around the earth,

00:21:47.330 --> 00:21:49.580
and you just always point
yourself away from the Earth.

00:21:49.580 --> 00:21:54.110
You'd sweep out a swath of
the sky that cover about 80%.

00:21:54.110 --> 00:21:56.310
We're not interested in
seeing only 80% of the sky.

00:21:56.310 --> 00:21:58.240
We want to see the whole sky.

00:21:58.240 --> 00:22:01.290
So what we do is we
tilt North for one orbit

00:22:01.290 --> 00:22:03.790
and cover the northern
hemisphere, and we tilt South

00:22:03.790 --> 00:22:06.750
for the second orbit to cover
the southern hemisphere,

00:22:06.750 --> 00:22:13.100
and what you see in this bottom
right-hand chart is the coverage

00:22:13.100 --> 00:22:16.300
of the sky over those two orbits.

00:22:16.300 --> 00:22:18.990
We see the entire sky
every three hours.

00:22:18.990 --> 00:22:21.680
And that's particularly important,

00:22:21.680 --> 00:22:25.060
because the gamma ray
sky is highly variable.

00:22:25.060 --> 00:22:30.130
Gamma ray bursts are popping off,
are active galaxies, are flaring,

00:22:30.130 --> 00:22:32.740
sometimes by changing their
flux by a factor of 100

00:22:32.740 --> 00:22:35.940
on time scales of hours or days.

00:22:35.940 --> 00:22:40.470
So here what I've done
is taken the Fermi sky

00:22:40.470 --> 00:22:44.150
and taken the northern hemisphere
and put it on the left-hand side

00:22:44.150 --> 00:22:47.350
and the southern hemisphere and
put it on the right-hand side,

00:22:47.350 --> 00:22:51.290
and the very bright galactic plane
is now a little bit suppressed.

00:22:51.290 --> 00:22:55.840
So you can see the other
things that are varying.

00:22:55.840 --> 00:22:58.750
Most of the things that you're
seeing are active galaxies.

00:22:58.750 --> 00:23:04.180
Super-massive black holes at very
large distances from us, with jets,

00:23:04.180 --> 00:23:08.310
relativistic jets, jets with
particles moving close to the speed

00:23:08.310 --> 00:23:11.840
of light pointing directly at us.

00:23:11.840 --> 00:23:15.320
You'll also notice that there seems
to be a source running around.

00:23:15.320 --> 00:23:19.050
This image is -- this movie is made

00:23:19.050 --> 00:23:20.890
of the sequence of
one-day snapshots.

00:23:20.890 --> 00:23:24.230
So this is what our sky
looks like every day.

00:23:24.230 --> 00:23:27.340
The object that's running
around is the sun.

00:23:27.340 --> 00:23:28.800
So, I mean, we can see it.

00:23:28.800 --> 00:23:31.950
It's not, you know, it's
not that it's not there,

00:23:31.950 --> 00:23:34.470
but it's certainly not as
bright as the optical sun.

00:23:34.470 --> 00:23:40.230 position:56%
I mean, imagine trying to take an
image of the sky when the sun is up.

00:23:40.230 --> 00:23:42.200
You certainly wouldn't
see any stars.

00:23:42.200 --> 00:23:45.690
I did mention earlier that the
moon is brighter than the sun,

00:23:45.690 --> 00:23:48.860
but of course, of these
timescales, the moon is moving

00:23:48.860 --> 00:23:51.140
through this image
much more quickly.

00:23:51.140 --> 00:23:54.540
So you're not seeing the
moon, because it's smearing

00:23:54.540 --> 00:23:58.340
across a larger number of pixels
on an integration time of a day.

00:23:58.340 --> 00:24:06.320
So I'm going to switch
gears a little and talk

00:24:06.320 --> 00:24:08.690
about one type of object.

00:24:08.690 --> 00:24:12.190
So if you start -- the
Earth is kind of small

00:24:12.190 --> 00:24:13.490
in the grand scheme of things.

00:24:13.490 --> 00:24:18.380
It's very important to us,
but we're really kind of tiny.

00:24:18.380 --> 00:24:23.470
And I'm showing this just to give
you a sense of the scale of size

00:24:23.470 --> 00:24:27.160
between the sun, the
moon, and the Earth.

00:24:27.160 --> 00:24:29.520
And I'm telling you this
because I want to give you a feel

00:24:29.520 --> 00:24:32.800
for how much -- how
large the sun is.

00:24:32.800 --> 00:24:37.430
Now imagine taking the sun and
compressing it to something

00:24:37.430 --> 00:24:39.460
that would fit inside DC.

00:24:39.460 --> 00:24:44.850
You'd have enormously
high densities.

00:24:44.850 --> 00:24:49.700
When you compress things, you
also compress the magnetic fields.

00:24:49.700 --> 00:24:51.610
So you end up with a
magnetic field that's more

00:24:51.610 --> 00:24:54.050
than a million times more intense

00:24:54.050 --> 00:24:56.100
than anything we can
produce on Earth.

00:24:56.100 --> 00:24:58.400
So now you have something
that's incredibly dense,

00:24:58.400 --> 00:25:02.520
with an incredibly high magnetic
field, and we spent rapidly.

00:25:02.520 --> 00:25:06.630
And by rapidly, think of
something like a ceiling fan.

00:25:06.630 --> 00:25:10.800
I mean, can you imagine something
that is the mass of the sun,

00:25:10.800 --> 00:25:15.030
the size of DC, and spinning
as rapidly as a ceiling fan?

00:25:15.030 --> 00:25:18.280
These are really extraordinary
objects.

00:25:18.280 --> 00:25:20.880
So it shouldn't surprise us
that this is the kind of place

00:25:20.880 --> 00:25:22.750
that gamma rays can be produced,

00:25:22.750 --> 00:25:24.050
because when we're
reducing gamma rays,

00:25:24.050 --> 00:25:26.620
we're looking for extremes
in the cosmos.

00:25:26.620 --> 00:25:28.390
We're looking for extremes
in magnetic fields,

00:25:28.390 --> 00:25:30.800
extreme energy, extreme
acceleration.

00:25:30.800 --> 00:25:35.930
We don't, in general, see stars in
gamma rays unless they're exploding

00:25:35.930 --> 00:25:39.580
or have exploded and they're in a
more energetic phase of their life.

00:25:39.580 --> 00:25:41.630
So what you're seeing
here is an animation

00:25:41.630 --> 00:25:44.870
of a rotating neutron star,
just to give you the sense

00:25:44.870 --> 00:25:47.850
of how you're going to
see a sequence of pulses

00:25:47.850 --> 00:25:52.690
from the emission be produced
at the two magnetic poles.

00:25:52.690 --> 00:25:57.270
Neutron stars are produced
in solar explosions.

00:25:57.270 --> 00:26:00.260
So you produce a neutron star
by starting with a normal star

00:26:00.260 --> 00:26:02.140
at the end of the star's life.

00:26:02.140 --> 00:26:05.010
It stops the nuclear burning.

00:26:05.010 --> 00:26:08.860
The material collapses on the
center into a huge explosion,

00:26:08.860 --> 00:26:15.290
and the remnant of this is either
a black hole or a neutron star.

00:26:18.750 --> 00:26:24.160
So this brings me to the very first
result that we had with Fermi.

00:26:24.160 --> 00:26:26.710
So October 16th is
our publication date,

00:26:26.710 --> 00:26:30.770
which means since we
started operations in August

00:26:30.770 --> 00:26:35.510
that this first result was based on
our first couple of weeks of data.

00:26:35.510 --> 00:26:42.890
What you see on the left-hand side
is the grayscale, is a radio image

00:26:42.890 --> 00:26:45.300
of the supernova remnants CTA1A.

00:26:45.300 --> 00:26:48.760
A supernova remnant
is the outer bits

00:26:48.760 --> 00:26:55.010
of the shock that's produced
when the star explodes.

00:26:55.010 --> 00:26:59.740
The blue circle is the
size of the uncertainty.

00:26:59.740 --> 00:27:03.120
So we knew that there is a gamma
ray source here, but we didn't know

00:27:03.120 --> 00:27:08.160
where it was better than the size
of this blue circle from six years

00:27:08.160 --> 00:27:11.000
of observation with the
previous instrument.

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:15.630
The red circle shows how well
we could pinpoint the location

00:27:15.630 --> 00:27:20.090
of this source with Fermi
after just two weeks of data.

00:27:20.090 --> 00:27:23.660
The red source lies right
on top of an x-ray source.

00:27:23.660 --> 00:27:26.190
So it's clear, at this point,
that the gamma ray source

00:27:26.190 --> 00:27:28.440
and the x-ray source really
must be the same thing.

00:27:28.440 --> 00:27:31.800
So the gamma ray is being, in
this case, were not being produced

00:27:31.800 --> 00:27:33.470
by the supernova remnant.

00:27:33.470 --> 00:27:39.780
They were being produced by
whatever that x-ray source was.

00:27:39.780 --> 00:27:42.040
Well, what makes this really
interesting is that when we looked

00:27:42.040 --> 00:27:46.060
at the data, we realized that
the pattern, the arrival time,

00:27:46.060 --> 00:27:50.690
of the gamma rays was not uniform.

00:27:50.690 --> 00:27:57.660
That every 316 milliseconds, we
were seeing the same patterns.

00:27:57.660 --> 00:28:03.140
So what you're seeing on here
is zero to 316 milliseconds

00:28:03.140 --> 00:28:05.810
and then were just repeating
the same thing again.

00:28:05.810 --> 00:28:11.520 position:56%
And this is telling us that for each
rotation of this star, this source,

00:28:11.520 --> 00:28:19.600 position:56%
is rotating at 316 milliseconds,
and that the gamma rays are arriving

00:28:19.600 --> 00:28:23.690
at the same point in
this rotation each time.

00:28:23.690 --> 00:28:25.740
So it's telling us
that this is a pulsar.

00:28:25.740 --> 00:28:30.150
But it's not a pulsar in radio.

00:28:30.150 --> 00:28:31.820
It's not a pulsar on x-rays.

00:28:31.820 --> 00:28:37.990
This was a pulsar shining only in
gamma rays, and that was telling us

00:28:37.990 --> 00:28:43.090
that we were never seeing the full
sample of pulsars in our galaxy,

00:28:43.090 --> 00:28:45.840
because before Fermi, we didn't
have an instrument that was able

00:28:45.840 --> 00:28:47.560
to find most of the pulsars.

00:28:47.560 --> 00:28:53.630
And they're important, because a
pulsar is the end stage of a star.

00:28:53.630 --> 00:28:56.710
So if we want to understand
the full lifecycle of a star,

00:28:56.710 --> 00:28:59.370
you have to understand them
from the birth right the way

00:28:59.370 --> 00:29:04.560
through to the death,
and this is the death.

00:29:04.560 --> 00:29:10.890
So this is an early degree
of PowerPointmenship.

00:29:10.890 --> 00:29:16.730 position:56%
So this is -- we've taken a bunch of
the early pulsars, manually put them

00:29:16.730 --> 00:29:19.780
onto the plot, and then
manually added an animation

00:29:19.780 --> 00:29:24.100
that is flashing 10 times
slower than the actual pulsar.

00:29:24.100 --> 00:29:28.280
But it illustrates what
we have in the sky.

00:29:28.280 --> 00:29:31.620
So CTA1 was just the
first of many pulsars

00:29:31.620 --> 00:29:33.530
that are found only in gamma ray's.

00:29:33.530 --> 00:29:36.430
We have over 60 that are
shining only in gamma rays.

00:29:36.430 --> 00:29:41.570 position:56%
About a third of the pulsars that
we know of shine only in gamma rays.

00:29:41.570 --> 00:29:43.450
We've also found 60 normal pulsars,

00:29:43.450 --> 00:29:46.640
the ones that are also
shining in radio.

00:29:46.640 --> 00:29:50.130
But you also notice on this image
that there's pulsars in pink

00:29:50.130 --> 00:29:51.470
that look like they're
just doing -- they're not.

00:29:51.470 --> 00:29:54.340
They're going very, very fast.

00:29:54.340 --> 00:29:59.330
Those are millisecond pulsars, and
those are a special kind of pulsar.

00:29:59.330 --> 00:30:03.050
They're pulsars that reach the
end of their lives, slow down,

00:30:03.050 --> 00:30:07.050
then they accreted material from a
companion that sped them up again

00:30:07.050 --> 00:30:10.510
until they were, again,
turned on his pulsars.

00:30:10.510 --> 00:30:13.960
They're known as millisecond
pulsars.

00:30:13.960 --> 00:30:17.300
They're very special objects,
and they're very special objects

00:30:17.300 --> 00:30:19.590
because they're excellent clocks.

00:30:19.590 --> 00:30:22.800
So one of the things that Fermi's
been able to do that over half

00:30:22.800 --> 00:30:29.270 position:56%
of the known millisecond pulsars
have been found from Fermi searches.

00:30:29.270 --> 00:30:32.060
And what we use millisecond
pulsars for is

00:30:32.060 --> 00:30:35.190 position:56%
that you've got something that's
spinning very, very, very regularly.

00:30:35.190 --> 00:30:39.090
So it's an excellent clock so if
you imagine you've got a very large

00:30:39.090 --> 00:30:40.390
gravitational wave coming

00:30:40.390 --> 00:30:43.660
through the galaxy that's
distorting space/time,

00:30:43.660 --> 00:30:47.860
it's going to slightly move the
arrival time of the radiation

00:30:47.860 --> 00:30:53.650 position:56%
from these millisecond pulsars, and
we can use that to chart the passage

00:30:53.650 --> 00:30:55.670
of very large gravitational waves.

00:30:55.670 --> 00:30:59.260 position:56%
So with this, we can create a galaxy
-sized gravitational wave detector.

00:30:59.260 --> 00:31:01.920
So this is just one
example of what you can do

00:31:01.920 --> 00:31:04.710
with the millisecond pulsars.

00:31:04.710 --> 00:31:07.320
We have another mystery.

00:31:07.320 --> 00:31:09.160
So this is not gamma rays.

00:31:09.160 --> 00:31:12.900
This is an optical image of our
galaxy, and the animation that I'm

00:31:12.900 --> 00:31:17.630
about to show is going to zoom in
towards the center of our galaxy.

00:31:17.630 --> 00:31:18.980
So this is close to the center.

00:31:18.980 --> 00:31:20.790
So not like the Fermi bubbles.

00:31:20.790 --> 00:31:28.700
Hang on. We need to
actually play it.

00:31:28.700 --> 00:31:34.270
As we get closer, this animation
will superimpose what we see

00:31:34.270 --> 00:31:35.730
at the galactic center.

00:31:35.730 --> 00:31:39.830
And as the animation
continues, all of the known ways

00:31:39.830 --> 00:31:41.890
to produce gamma ray's
will be subtracted.

00:31:41.890 --> 00:31:43.480
Subtract the background.

00:31:43.480 --> 00:31:49.480 position:56%
We'll subtract the point sources,
and what you get left with is a blob

00:31:49.480 --> 00:31:54.390
about 10 degrees in size
that is also unexpected.

00:31:54.390 --> 00:31:57.060
It has an unusual spectrum,
and by spectrum,

00:31:57.060 --> 00:32:00.490
I just mean the distribution
of energies off the gamma rays.

00:32:00.490 --> 00:32:03.190
It just peaks between 1 and 5 GeV.

00:32:03.190 --> 00:32:06.310
A supernova remnant
doesn't behave like that.

00:32:06.310 --> 00:32:10.180
A pulsar can, but a pulsar
isn't 10 degrees in size.

00:32:10.180 --> 00:32:14.080
So this is one of the second
mysteries that we have

00:32:14.080 --> 00:32:15.680
at the center of our galaxy.

00:32:15.680 --> 00:32:20.380
That the center of our galaxy
is special, because that's

00:32:20.380 --> 00:32:24.340
where the largest gravitational
sync is.

00:32:24.340 --> 00:32:29.440
You might have heard of
the mystery of dark matter.

00:32:29.440 --> 00:32:33.410
That there is a material in
our galaxy, there is material

00:32:33.410 --> 00:32:39.260
and galaxy clusters beyond what
we can actually see radiating.

00:32:39.260 --> 00:32:43.370
And our colleagues from
particle physics tell us

00:32:43.370 --> 00:32:46.730
that the leading candidate for
dark matter, because it solves one

00:32:46.730 --> 00:32:50.130
of their particle physics
problems, is a new particle

00:32:50.130 --> 00:32:54.410
that when it encounters
itself, will produce gamma rays.

00:32:54.410 --> 00:32:56.630
Where would you expect to find the
most dark matter in our galaxy?

00:32:56.630 --> 00:32:58.330
Right at the center.

00:32:58.330 --> 00:32:59.750
How would you expect
it to be distributed?

00:32:59.750 --> 00:33:02.390
You'd expect it to be
distributed in a blob.

00:33:02.390 --> 00:33:03.900
What would you expect
the spectrum to be?

00:33:03.900 --> 00:33:08.340
You'd expect it to be peaked
and have a sharp cut off related

00:33:08.340 --> 00:33:12.490
to the size of the
dark matter particle.

00:33:12.490 --> 00:33:17.770
So one exciting possibility is that
what we're seeing here is a signal

00:33:17.770 --> 00:33:19.810
of dark matter in gamma rays.

00:33:19.810 --> 00:33:23.220
If we look at our neighboring
galaxy, Andromeda.

00:33:23.220 --> 00:33:27.780
So this is a very recent result
published earlier this year,

00:33:27.780 --> 00:33:30.180
we found the same thing
in Andromeda.

00:33:30.180 --> 00:33:32.220
So what you're saying
on the left-hand side,

00:33:32.220 --> 00:33:39.930
the contour lines chart where
the gas in that galaxy is.

00:33:39.930 --> 00:33:43.730
If the gamma rays in
Andromeda are produced

00:33:43.730 --> 00:33:47.720
by very high energy
particles smashing into gas,

00:33:47.720 --> 00:33:50.710
then the gamma rays should
be following the pattern

00:33:50.710 --> 00:33:52.850
of those lines.

00:33:52.850 --> 00:33:54.150
And it is not.

00:33:54.150 --> 00:33:57.630
The gamma rays are concentrated
at the center of that galaxy.

00:33:57.630 --> 00:33:59.980
So like our galaxy, Andromeda has

00:33:59.980 --> 00:34:05.700
in an anomalously bright
emission of gamma rays.

00:34:05.700 --> 00:34:10.060
Like our galaxy, Andromeda sees
the same distribution of energies.

00:34:10.060 --> 00:34:13.550
So whatever we see in the center
of our galaxy is not unique

00:34:13.550 --> 00:34:16.760
to our galaxy, but is a
phenomenon that's likely present

00:34:16.760 --> 00:34:19.080
in all normal galaxies.

00:34:19.080 --> 00:34:24.360
So this is potentially very
exciting, and it, you know,

00:34:24.360 --> 00:34:28.210
we're still excited at the
prospect of this being dark matter,

00:34:28.210 --> 00:34:32.110
but you have to always
consider other possibilities.

00:34:32.110 --> 00:34:34.200
And now that we know that
there's a large number of pulsars

00:34:34.200 --> 00:34:38.410
in our galaxy, it's possible
that we've a large population

00:34:38.410 --> 00:34:41.290
of millisecond pulsars around
the center of our galaxy,

00:34:41.290 --> 00:34:43.090
and from my perspective,
it doesn't really matter

00:34:43.090 --> 00:34:45.690
which of these perspectives
are correct.

00:34:45.690 --> 00:34:49.610
I think it's incredibly
exciting that the center

00:34:49.610 --> 00:34:53.110
of our galaxy had activity
several million years ago

00:34:53.110 --> 00:34:55.790
that we didn't know about,
and that now the center

00:34:55.790 --> 00:34:59.240
of our galaxy contains components
that we didn't know about.

00:34:59.240 --> 00:35:03.790
I'm going to switch
gears completely.

00:35:03.790 --> 00:35:06.840
Everything I've spoken
about so far our data

00:35:06.840 --> 00:35:08.250
from the large area telescope.

00:35:08.250 --> 00:35:10.690
That's this box up at the top.

00:35:10.690 --> 00:35:13.630
But there's other instrumentation
on Fermi.

00:35:13.630 --> 00:35:15.110 position:56%
We have the gamma ray burst monitor.

00:35:15.110 --> 00:35:19.350
It's an array of instruments.

00:35:19.350 --> 00:35:21.590
There's three here, one
here, another three,

00:35:21.590 --> 00:35:24.550
and the same on the other
side of the spacecraft.

00:35:24.550 --> 00:35:28.080
And his instrument is designed
to detect flashes of gamma rays

00:35:28.080 --> 00:35:31.750 position:56%
at lower energies then the Fermi
telescope, but large-area telescope.

00:35:31.750 --> 00:35:35.390
So what kind of things do we see?

00:35:35.390 --> 00:35:39.030
Well, a gamma ray burst,
I've already mentioned,

00:35:39.030 --> 00:35:44.670 position:56%
is the birth of a black hole, either
because two neutron stars merge

00:35:44.670 --> 00:35:46.940
or a neutron star and
a black hole merge,

00:35:46.940 --> 00:35:52.230
or a large star has an
extremely energetic supernova.

00:35:53.880 --> 00:35:55.400
There's an object known
as a magnetar,

00:35:55.400 --> 00:36:00.230
and a magnetar is an extremely
high magnetic field neutron star,

00:36:00.230 --> 00:36:04.260
and when you crack the crossed
and have a sudden large release

00:36:04.260 --> 00:36:07.660
of magnetic energy, you get
a large burst of gamma rays

00:36:07.660 --> 00:36:09.900
that the whole star is shaking.

00:36:09.900 --> 00:36:12.800
So the gamma rays are coming
out in a periodic motion,

00:36:12.800 --> 00:36:14.750
but this periodic motion
isn't telling us

00:36:14.750 --> 00:36:16.100
about the rotation of the magnetar.

00:36:16.100 --> 00:36:19.230 position:56%
This periodic motion is telling us
about the structure and the interior

00:36:19.230 --> 00:36:23.480
of the star, just as the sound
you get from a bell is determined

00:36:23.480 --> 00:36:25.610
by the material of the
bell and its shape.

00:36:25.610 --> 00:36:30.980
We can use the time, the pattern
of the signal from the gamma rays

00:36:30.980 --> 00:36:33.810
from magnetars to explore
the interior structure

00:36:33.810 --> 00:36:35.130
of a neutron star.

00:36:35.130 --> 00:36:39.090
We see gamma ray flashes
from the sun,

00:36:39.090 --> 00:36:43.470
less now that the sun isn't
active, and the topic that I want

00:36:43.470 --> 00:36:45.370
to focus on, because I
thought I'd do something other

00:36:45.370 --> 00:36:48.580 position:56%
than astrophysics, or thunderstorms.

00:36:48.580 --> 00:36:53.370
Because the Fermi gamma ray burst
monitor sees the entire sky,

00:36:53.370 --> 00:36:56.570
most of it is the sky, but
the earth is underneath us.

00:36:56.570 --> 00:36:58.080
So we don't see the
sky through the earth.

00:36:58.080 --> 00:36:59.560
We see the Earth.

00:36:59.560 --> 00:37:03.980
And when the spacecraft is
over regions of the earth

00:37:03.980 --> 00:37:08.970
that have thunderstorm systems,
we quite often see a very short,

00:37:08.970 --> 00:37:13.340
brief flash of gamma rays,
lasting just milliseconds,

00:37:13.340 --> 00:37:14.930 position:56%
with a very characteristic spectrum,

00:37:14.930 --> 00:37:18.460
very characteristic
distribution of energies.

00:37:18.460 --> 00:37:23.270
And if you plot these
unusual transients in the sky,

00:37:23.270 --> 00:37:26.300
you'll find that they
lie on top of regions

00:37:26.300 --> 00:37:27.600
where there were thunderstorms.

00:37:27.600 --> 00:37:29.370
This was the moment where I learned

00:37:29.370 --> 00:37:31.930
that thunderstorms
happen largely overland.

00:37:31.930 --> 00:37:37.280
I think it's kind of
obvious from this.

00:37:37.280 --> 00:37:38.660
But what's interesting is a handful

00:37:38.660 --> 00:37:41.370
of them show very unusual
properties.

00:37:41.370 --> 00:37:45.910
So we had a situation where
the spacecraft was above Egypt,

00:37:45.910 --> 00:37:50.060
and we saw one of these
terrestrial gamma ray flashes,

00:37:50.060 --> 00:37:52.680
flashes of gamma rays
produced in thunderstorms.

00:37:52.680 --> 00:37:57.710
But there wasn't any thunderstorms
in Egypt, but there were

00:37:57.710 --> 00:38:02.920
in Tanzania, and if
we look at the --

00:38:02.920 --> 00:38:04.580
there's two things I
want you to look at.

00:38:04.580 --> 00:38:07.870
The first is the --
on the left-hand side,

00:38:07.870 --> 00:38:11.050
what you're seeing here is
time on the x axis and counts,

00:38:11.050 --> 00:38:15.710
number of gamma rays on the right
excess, and what we saw was a peak,

00:38:15.710 --> 00:38:18.780
and then it came down, and then
we saw another little peak.

00:38:18.780 --> 00:38:23.220
And that's unusual, but what
I really want you to look

00:38:23.220 --> 00:38:24.630
at is on the right-hand side.

00:38:24.630 --> 00:38:28.380
On the right-hand side what you
see is energy along the x axis

00:38:28.380 --> 00:38:32.380
and the number of gamma rays
on the right on the y axis,

00:38:32.380 --> 00:38:34.580
and this sharp spectral feature.

00:38:34.580 --> 00:38:39.910
The energy of that
bump is at 511 KeV.

00:38:39.910 --> 00:38:48.780
That's exactly half the
energy of an electron.

00:38:48.780 --> 00:38:53.030
What's happening here isn't that
we're seeing gamma ray's directly.

00:38:53.030 --> 00:38:57.160 position:56%
What's happening is the positrons
are directly hitting the instrument,

00:38:57.160 --> 00:38:58.460
are converting.

00:38:58.460 --> 00:39:02.180
It's a positron is the
antimatter particles, the electron.

00:39:02.180 --> 00:39:04.550
They're hitting electrons
in our detector,

00:39:04.550 --> 00:39:07.230
and they're doing the
opposite of the pair conversion

00:39:07.230 --> 00:39:08.530
that I spoke about before.

00:39:08.530 --> 00:39:11.260
So E still equals MC
squared, but in his case,

00:39:11.260 --> 00:39:13.980
we're turning the matter
back into gamma rays,

00:39:13.980 --> 00:39:18.510
and then we're detecting those
gamma rays in the instrument.

00:39:18.510 --> 00:39:20.850
This also was a surprise.

00:39:20.850 --> 00:39:23.170
So you go back to the drawing
board and you think, well,

00:39:23.170 --> 00:39:26.570
what was -- what's going on here?

00:39:26.570 --> 00:39:30.880
So this image shows a
thunderstorm on Earth.

00:39:30.880 --> 00:39:34.570
The moon is there just for context,

00:39:34.570 --> 00:39:43.520
and in the thunderstorm,
the pink are gamma rays.

00:39:43.520 --> 00:39:46.490
So what you have is
an enormous amount

00:39:46.490 --> 00:39:48.070 position:56%
of acceleration in the thunderstorm.

00:39:48.070 --> 00:39:50.400
The thunderstorm is
accelerating particles.

00:39:50.400 --> 00:39:53.260
The particles are producing
gamma rays in the atmosphere.

00:39:53.260 --> 00:39:57.000
But the accelerated
particles, when they move --

00:39:57.000 --> 00:39:58.600
when particles move
in a magnetic field,

00:39:58.600 --> 00:40:00.040
they have to follow the
magnetic field line.

00:40:00.040 --> 00:40:02.870
So the charged particles are

00:40:02.870 --> 00:40:06.600
in yellow can't spray
out in all directions.

00:40:06.600 --> 00:40:09.060
They are following the
magnetic field line.

00:40:09.060 --> 00:40:12.930
So we move onto the next
animation, now you can start

00:40:12.930 --> 00:40:14.950
to get a sense of what happened.

00:40:14.950 --> 00:40:17.330
The thunderstorm happened
in Tanzania.

00:40:17.330 --> 00:40:20.050
You've got a pulse
of charged particles.

00:40:20.050 --> 00:40:22.660
This is a pulse of
electrons and positrons

00:40:22.660 --> 00:40:25.730
that are traveling along the
magnetic field line thousands

00:40:25.730 --> 00:40:27.990
of miles, hitting our spacecraft.

00:40:27.990 --> 00:40:30.310
And they're continuing along
the magnetic field line

00:40:30.310 --> 00:40:33.020
until they reach the conjugate
point, at which they bounce

00:40:33.020 --> 00:40:35.870
and come back and hit
the spacecraft again.

00:40:35.870 --> 00:40:37.200
So this is the same
kind of phenomenon

00:40:37.200 --> 00:40:41.190
that keeps charged particles
in the Van Allen belt.

00:40:41.190 --> 00:40:47.100
I find it quite amazing to realize
that even if you're thousands

00:40:47.100 --> 00:40:49.580
of miles away from something, that
a thunderstorm is affecting us

00:40:49.580 --> 00:40:53.440
by sending antimatter directly to
us from thousands of miles away.

00:40:53.440 --> 00:40:55.220
So I'm almost finished.

00:40:55.220 --> 00:40:58.460
I'm not going to talk about all
the other things that we do,

00:40:58.460 --> 00:41:03.160
but we have done and continue
to do extraordinary things.

00:41:03.160 --> 00:41:09.040
So what I'm showing here, starting
on the bottom left, close to us,

00:41:09.040 --> 00:41:12.610
and going up to the top
right to most distant

00:41:12.610 --> 00:41:16.530
from us are all the
astrophysical topics

00:41:16.530 --> 00:41:21.010
that Fermi has produced
a press release on.

00:41:21.010 --> 00:41:23.750
Everything in yellow are
things that were not known

00:41:23.750 --> 00:41:26.060
as gamma ray emitters
before the launch of Fermi.

00:41:26.060 --> 00:41:27.910
So we have it just seemed
more gamma ray sources.

00:41:27.910 --> 00:41:32.280
We haven't just measured known
gamma ray sources more precisely.

00:41:32.280 --> 00:41:34.790
We have understood the
energetic universe in a way

00:41:34.790 --> 00:41:37.580
that we had no idea
before launching Fermi.

00:41:37.580 --> 00:41:39.950
This has opened our
eyes and hold new ways.

00:41:39.950 --> 00:41:44.870
And I am pleased that we are
able to address the questions

00:41:44.870 --> 00:41:49.140
that we said we would address
when we launched the instrument,

00:41:49.140 --> 00:41:53.650 position:56%
but I think, as a scientist, what
makes me most excited about Fermi is

00:41:53.650 --> 00:41:56.150
that we've raised new questions.

00:41:56.150 --> 00:41:58.010
We know the Fermi bubbles
exist, but we don't know

00:41:58.010 --> 00:42:01.160
yet precisely what causes them.

00:42:01.160 --> 00:42:03.620
We know that we've got an excess of
gamma rays in our galactic center,

00:42:03.620 --> 00:42:07.090
but we don't know what
that excess is.

00:42:07.090 --> 00:42:13.500 position:56%
I could have given this talk and
covered a completely different range

00:42:13.500 --> 00:42:17.800
of topics, and I sometimes do,
and I think they would've been,

00:42:17.800 --> 00:42:23.890
at least to me, just as compelling
as what I've described to you here.

00:42:23.890 --> 00:42:26.000
So I think my summary is
to say that, you know,

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:27.550
really there's much
more to the universe

00:42:27.550 --> 00:42:29.260
and we can see with our eyes.

00:42:29.260 --> 00:42:34.830
This is true on earth just as
much is it's true in the cosmos.

00:42:34.830 --> 00:42:37.400
My day job is extremely exciting,

00:42:37.400 --> 00:42:41.130
because our observatory is
constantly scanning the entire sky,

00:42:41.130 --> 00:42:42.790
and the sky is constantly changing.

00:42:42.790 --> 00:42:45.100
So there's always something
new to fine.

00:42:45.100 --> 00:42:47.940
I talked about two unexpected and
different features in our galaxy.

00:42:47.940 --> 00:42:50.850
We have huge lobes of tens of
thousands of light-years in size,

00:42:50.850 --> 00:42:53.770
and then we have this unexpected
blob right at the center

00:42:53.770 --> 00:42:57.700
of our galaxy, both of which
have potentially extremely

00:42:57.700 --> 00:42:59.230
exciting explanations.

00:42:59.230 --> 00:43:03.330
The first is that the galactic
center was not as calm and quiet

00:43:03.330 --> 00:43:09.140
in the near past as it is now,
and the other might be a signal

00:43:09.140 --> 00:43:12.040
of dark matter or might be
telling us about a whole population

00:43:12.040 --> 00:43:14.860
of objects close to the center
of our galaxy that we know about.

00:43:14.860 --> 00:43:19.250 position:56%
And there's a ton of things I
didn't discuss, but what can you do?

00:43:19.250 --> 00:43:21.510
Thank you.

